# Your First Utilities

The single most valuable Tailwind skill is **reading a class string fluently** — looking at
`flex items-center gap-4 rounded-lg bg-white p-6 shadow` and *seeing the box it describes*. Let's
build that skill deliberately.

## The anatomy of a utility

Most utilities follow a simple grammar: **`property-value`** or **`property-side-value`**.

<CodeBlock
	language="html"
	filename="reading utilities"
	code={`text-lg       /* font-size: large            */
font-bold     /* font-weight: 700            */
text-blue-600 /* color: a specific blue      */
p-4           /* padding: 1rem on all sides  */
px-4          /* padding-left + padding-right */
mt-2          /* margin-top: 0.5rem          */
gap-3         /* gap between flex/grid items */`}
/>

Notice the shorthands: `p` = padding, `m` = margin, `x` = horizontal, `y` = vertical, `t/r/b/l` =
top/right/bottom/left. Once you know the grammar, you can *guess* class names correctly — that's the
goal.

## The spacing scale

Numbers like `p-4` aren't pixels — they're steps on a **scale**. `1` = `0.25rem` (4px), `2` =
`0.5rem` (8px), `4` = `1rem` (16px), and so on. Because everyone draws from the same scale,
spacing across an app stays harmonious.

<CodeBlock
	playground
	filename="spacing scale"
	code={`<div class="space-y-2">
  <div class="bg-blue-200 p-1">p-1 = 4px</div>
  <div class="bg-blue-200 p-2">p-2 = 8px</div>
  <div class="bg-blue-200 p-4">p-4 = 16px</div>
  <div class="bg-blue-200 p-8">p-8 = 32px</div>
</div>`}
/>

## Composing a real element

Watch how a handful of utilities combine into a finished UI element. Open the playground and try
changing `rounded-lg` to `rounded-full`, or `shadow` to `shadow-xl`.

<CodeBlock
	playground
	filename="a card"
	code={`<div class="max-w-sm rounded-xl bg-white p-6 shadow-md">
  <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900">Reading is a superpower</h2>
  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-500">
    You just composed padding, radius, shadow, color and type — entirely in markup.
  </p>
  <button class="mt-4 rounded-lg bg-blue-600 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-white">
    Nice
  </button>
</div>`}
/>

<Callout type="tip" title="Don't memorise — recognise">

You do not need to memorise every class. Install the **Tailwind CSS IntelliSense** extension and
you'll get autocomplete with a live preview of each value. Your job is to learn the *grammar* so
autocomplete becomes a conversation, not a guessing game.

</Callout>

<Callout type="insight" title="Constraints are a feature, not a limitation">

Beginners often want `margin-top: 13px`. Tailwind nudges you to `mt-3` (12px) or `mt-4` (16px). That
friction is intentional. A constrained scale eliminates a whole category of "why is this 1px off"
bugs and design drift. As a lead, you'll come to value tools that make the *consistent* choice the
*default* choice — it's how you keep quality high without policing every pull request.

</Callout>

